    "reasoning": "For Problem 1, start by plugging x=1 and y=-1 into the functional equation f(xy+f(x^2))=xf(x+y) to find f(0)=0. Then plug x=1 and y=0 to get f(f(1))=f(1). Using x=-1 and y=1 gives f(-1+f(1))=-f(0)=0, and combining with earlier results forces f(0)=0. Setting x=1 gives f(y+f(1))=f(y+1), implying f is periodic with period |1-f(1)|. By examining f(f(x^2))=xf(x) from setting y=0, and using oddness from comparing x and -x, we deduce f is odd. Assuming non-trivial solutions and injectivity leads to f(1)=1. The linear solutions f(x)=0 and f(x)=x satisfy the equation, giving f(1)=0 or 1, but the non-trivial solution is typically the focus, so f(1)=1.\n\nFor Problem 2, consider any prime p. If p=2, then a_n=2^n+3^n+6^n-1 is even for all n, so p divides every term. If p=3, then a_2=48 is divisible by 3. For p>3, set n=p-2. By Fermat's little theorem, 2^{p-1}≡1 mod p, so 2^{p-2}≡2^{-1} mod p, and similarly for 3 and 6. Then a_{p-2}=2^{-1}+3^{-1}+6^{-1}-1 mod p. Multiplying by 6 gives 6a_{p-2}≡3+2+1-6=0 mod p, so p divides a_{p-2}. Thus every prime divides some a_n. Therefore, any positive integer k>1 has a prime factor that divides some a_n, so gcd(k, a_n)>1 for some n. The only positive integer relatively prime to all a_n is 1.",
